{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502721"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:49:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1893"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1893"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.07,0.33,0.42,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1893"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1893"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2152"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a two-week history of malaise, arthralgia of multiple joints, myalgia and sweats. He remembers experiencing a similar thing over summer a few months ago, but just thought it was due to the hot weather. Prior to this, he had never experienced symptoms like this before. He does not complain of any pain elsewhere, changes in bowel motions, nausea/vomiting, muscle weakness, or headaches. He has a medical history significant for hypertension and takes ramipril. He also has a right exotropia, which he has had for as long as he can remember. On examination, he has a rash (Image) and a temperature of 38.2\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parvovirus infection","Carcinoid syndrome","Dermatomyositis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Erysipelas"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows the classical \u0027butterfly rash\u0027 that is associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Esystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E (SLE). Furthermore, a history of arthralgia, myalgia, and malaise supports systemic involvement noted in SLE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParvovirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a similar \u0027slapped-cheek\u0027 appearance; however, this is usually only present in children. Older individuals usually present with minimal symptoms; joint pain and muscle aches with fever is classical of parvovirus infection in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoid syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a group of symptoms that appear due to carcinoid tumours. A carcinoid tumour is a neuroendocrine tumour that can develop in the gastrointestinal tract and lungs. Flushing is an episodic transient rash that can involve various parts of the body in carcinoid syndrome depending on the location of the neuroendocrine tumour. Other associated symptoms includes diarrhoea, vomiting, nausea, shortness of breath and palpitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory condition that presents with muscle weakness and rash, particularly on the extremities and face. It is less commonly associated with fever. Absence of muscle weakness alone cannot exclude diagnosis of this condition, however, butterfly rash is not associated with dermatomyositis. Classic sites of involvement includes eyelids, chest, upper back, dorsum of fingers and hands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErysipelas\u003C/strong\u003E is a bacterial infection similar to cellulitis; however, affecting the upper dermis only. It presents with a raised, well defined, tender, warm rash, and most commonly presents on the face and legs. It would be unusual for erysipelas to present with bilateral cheek involvement as well as multiple systemic symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A facial rash and systemic symptoms of myalgia and arthralgia should raise the possible diagnosis of SLE.","The \u0027butterfly rash\u0027 is a classic dermatological manifestation of systemic lupus erythematosus."],"references":["Rubin de Celis Ferrari AC, Glasberg J, Riechelmann RP. Carcinoid syndrome: update on the pathophysiology and treatment. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Aug 20;73(suppl 1):e490s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e490s. PMID: 30133565; PMCID: PMC6096975. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30133565/","Justiz Vaillant AA, Goyal A, Bansal P, et al. Systemic Lupus Erythematosus. [Updated 2020 Dec 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535405/","Fava A, Petri M. Systemic lupus erythematosus: Diagnosis and clinical management. J Autoimmun. 2019 Jan;96:1-13. doi: 10.1016/j.jaut.2018.11.001. Epub 2018 Nov 16. PMID: 30448290; PMCID: PMC6310637. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30448290/","Uva L, Miguel D, Pinheiro C, Freitas JP, Marques Gomes M, Filipe P. Cutaneous manifestations of systemic lupus erythematosus. Autoimmune Dis. 2012;2012:834291. doi: 10.1155/2012/834291. Epub 2012 Jul 25. PMID: 22888407; PMCID: PMC3410306. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22888407/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1893"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17578"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17578"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/95b967f8-71fd-44cf-9066-ee0c7cf75dab.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/95b967f8-71fd-44cf-9066-ee0c7cf75dab.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-22T14:58:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-22T14:59:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1893"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":""